WEBVTT

00:02.097 --> 00:05.597
(film projector whirring)

00:10.013 --> 00:13.096
(gentle piano music)

00:20.090 --> 00:22.480
- Oh, yeah. I don't think I'm gonna go.

00:22.480 --> 00:24.533
I'll just stay here, watch a movie.

00:27.220 --> 00:30.995
I know, I know. I never go
out with you guys anymore.

00:30.995 --> 00:33.995
(suspenseful music)

00:45.410 --> 00:46.920
Listen...

00:46.920 --> 00:49.063
I'm dying for some me time.

00:49.063 --> 00:50.963
I just really need to stay in tonight.

00:51.852 --> 00:54.519
(ominous music)

00:57.390 --> 00:58.393
I know.

00:59.900 --> 01:00.850
I know.

01:00.850 --> 01:03.015
Me and my excuses.

01:03.015 --> 01:05.682
(ominous music)

01:07.110 --> 01:08.683
Okay. Have a drink for me.

01:09.600 --> 01:11.623
You guys have fun and be safe.

01:13.100 --> 01:14.250
All right, bye.

01:16.606 --> 01:17.590
(suspenseful music)

01:17.590 --> 01:20.282
(tapping on window)

01:20.282 --> 01:22.949
(ominous music)

01:45.977 --> 01:48.644
(water running)

01:53.451 --> 01:56.451
(suspenseful music)

02:04.899 --> 02:05.732
Hello?

02:12.201 --> 02:14.868
(door creaking)

02:25.523 --> 02:28.356
(startling music)

02:39.340 --> 02:41.800
(pad slaps table)

02:41.800 --> 02:42.883
- Why is she naked?

02:43.920 --> 02:46.090
- Do you shower with clothes on?

02:46.090 --> 02:49.390
- I don't, but Mary Rose
was not found in her home,

02:49.390 --> 02:52.440
and she was not nude when
they discovered her body,

02:52.440 --> 02:56.490
so I'm wondering why she's
getting naked in this scenario.

02:56.490 --> 02:58.880
- Look, horror fans want certain things

02:58.880 --> 03:00.610
in their films, okay?

03:00.610 --> 03:01.443
- Tits?

03:02.360 --> 03:04.160
- Among other things.

03:04.160 --> 03:05.660
- Like, what else?

03:05.660 --> 03:08.790
- Blood, clowns, and incest hillbillies,

03:08.790 --> 03:11.430
which you two shot down immediately!

03:11.430 --> 03:12.300
- I'm still against those.

03:12.300 --> 03:15.083
- I still feel fine about
that decision, by the way.

03:15.083 --> 03:16.250
- Fine.

03:16.250 --> 03:17.510
- Before we proceed any further,

03:17.510 --> 03:21.280
I've mentioned this before, but
I'm just gonna say it again.

03:21.280 --> 03:22.840
Is this exploitative?

03:22.840 --> 03:25.910
- Since when did showing a
beautiful woman's body on camera

03:25.910 --> 03:27.320
become exploitative?

03:27.320 --> 03:29.050
- I'm not talking about the nude scene.

03:29.050 --> 03:32.220
I'm talking about writing a horror movie

03:32.220 --> 03:34.540
about murders that are
taking place, you know,

03:34.540 --> 03:38.850
among our neighbors and community
in the very recent past.

03:38.850 --> 03:41.110
- You're right. You're right.

03:41.110 --> 03:43.730
We'll get a few angry emails,
a couple of bad reviews,

03:43.730 --> 03:46.070
but look, guys, this is gonna be huge!

03:46.070 --> 03:48.340
Think about it. Who's done this before?

03:48.340 --> 03:50.980
A movie about a murderer
that's still at large.

03:50.980 --> 03:54.173
Think about it. You're in the
theater watching this movie.

03:55.300 --> 03:57.883
Who's that? Is that your friend, John?

03:59.490 --> 04:00.690
Or is that the murderer?

04:02.060 --> 04:03.243
- That's interesting.

04:04.490 --> 04:06.510
- I don't wanna step on
anybody's toes or anything,

04:06.510 --> 04:08.140
and I'm not a writer,

04:08.140 --> 04:11.910
but I am a little nervous about
looking into these murders

04:11.910 --> 04:13.430
with them still being active.

04:13.430 --> 04:15.180
There's a lot of stuff we don't know.

04:15.180 --> 04:18.170
- Right, we wanna make sure
that it's told correctly,

04:18.170 --> 04:19.930
for one thing.

04:19.930 --> 04:22.120
Of course, I also have
concerns about the fact

04:22.120 --> 04:25.293
that the story doesn't have an ending.

04:26.660 --> 04:28.232
- That's true.

04:28.232 --> 04:30.060
- One the one hand,
yes, that's very scary.

04:30.060 --> 04:32.183
He could still be among us and all that.

04:33.210 --> 04:34.043
On the other hand,

04:34.043 --> 04:36.490
we had three murders within four months

04:36.490 --> 04:38.483
and then four months of nothing.

04:40.340 --> 04:42.360
- That's where you come in.

04:42.360 --> 04:44.300
Look, we know a lot about what's going on,

04:44.300 --> 04:47.000
but it's safe to say that
there's a lot we don't know.

04:48.960 --> 04:50.783
I say we spice it up a little bit.

04:51.840 --> 04:55.150
Take a few artistic liberties.

04:55.150 --> 04:56.900
- It could be artsy.

04:56.900 --> 04:59.090
- Spice, okay, so...

05:00.540 --> 05:02.410
What are you thinking?

05:02.410 --> 05:05.223
- Well, now that you
ask, just bear with me.

05:06.260 --> 05:10.100
Our killer. This is
all just a game to him.

05:10.100 --> 05:13.510
But guess what? Regular season's over.

05:13.510 --> 05:14.590
He's clenched his division.

05:14.590 --> 05:17.490
He's in the playoffs with a bye week.

05:17.490 --> 05:18.930
- I don't do sports.

05:18.930 --> 05:21.210
- I follow you.

05:21.210 --> 05:22.133
- He's planning.

05:23.130 --> 05:27.690
Preparing for his next
big game. His Super Bowl.

05:27.690 --> 05:31.270
A fucking blood bath!

05:31.270 --> 05:32.150
- Okay, but...

05:33.260 --> 05:35.310
Where's all the blood coming from?

05:35.310 --> 05:37.150
There was dismemberment, yes.

05:37.150 --> 05:39.770
There are parts missing
from the bodies found,

05:39.770 --> 05:42.330
but the actual cause of
death was strangulation.

05:42.330 --> 05:44.083
The mutilation was posthumous.

05:45.940 --> 05:46.773
- She's right.

05:47.650 --> 05:50.470
- Look, do you guys
wanna make a documentary

05:50.470 --> 05:52.210
or a good movie?

05:52.210 --> 05:54.000
- I'm sorry that these women's deaths

05:54.000 --> 05:56.200
were not exciting enough for you, Seth!

05:56.200 --> 05:58.560
- That's not what I meant.

05:58.560 --> 06:00.550
- We don't know a lot
about the people involved.

06:00.550 --> 06:02.330
Maybe there needs to be some research.

06:02.330 --> 06:03.970
Like the killer, we don't even know

06:03.970 --> 06:05.310
is he a good guy, bad guy?

06:05.310 --> 06:06.390
- They're not a good person.

06:06.390 --> 06:07.890
- He's a psychopath.

06:07.890 --> 06:10.530
- Well, I mean, maybe, yeah.

06:10.530 --> 06:11.940
It's worth mentioning, like you said,

06:11.940 --> 06:14.653
there haven't been any
deaths in several months.

06:15.780 --> 06:17.423
He could be done.

06:18.990 --> 06:19.823
- Yeah.

06:21.300 --> 06:23.260
All right, so we're talking
about spinning an ending

06:23.260 --> 06:25.270
out of thin air.

06:25.270 --> 06:26.250
We'll write down ideas,

06:26.250 --> 06:30.000
make sure that everybody
feels heard in the scenario.

06:30.000 --> 06:32.630
I'm putting Seth down for a blood bath,

06:32.630 --> 06:34.480
total effing blood bath.

06:34.480 --> 06:35.570
- Thank you.

06:35.570 --> 06:37.320
- And Mark...

06:37.320 --> 06:38.390
Done.

06:38.390 --> 06:39.990
- Done.

06:39.990 --> 06:42.253
- I'm just gonna write that. Done.

06:44.280 --> 06:46.130
- And on that exciting note,

06:46.130 --> 06:47.680
I think we're done for the day.

06:50.123 --> 06:52.623
(car dinging)

06:54.031 --> 06:56.698
(anxious music)

08:16.848 --> 08:19.598
(dramatic music)

08:35.172 --> 08:37.922
(tinkling music)

09:01.335 --> 09:04.347
♪ My heart will fly to heaven ♪

09:04.347 --> 09:07.869
♪ On the day he'll be mine ♪

09:07.869 --> 09:11.416
♪ We'll be standing on the threshold ♪

09:11.416 --> 09:15.117
♪ Of a moment divine ♪

09:15.117 --> 09:18.460
♪ And from that day forever ♪

09:18.460 --> 09:22.027
♪ We will leave hand in hand ♪

09:22.027 --> 09:24.150
♪ It's the day of days ♪

09:24.150 --> 09:29.150
♪ The one for which I've
dreamed and I've planned ♪

09:46.122 --> 09:49.955
(sentimental orchestra music)

09:52.060 --> 09:53.430
- [Mara] Quickly, Truson!

09:53.430 --> 09:55.410
I have a key! The jailer's a friend!

09:55.410 --> 09:56.440
You must escape!

09:56.440 --> 09:57.923
- [Truson] I can't leave. No.

09:59.196 --> 10:02.460
- [Mara] But why? I want to go with you!

10:02.460 --> 10:03.650
- [Truson] No, Mara.

10:03.650 --> 10:05.760
Running away is not the solution.

10:05.760 --> 10:07.400
Don't you see?

10:07.400 --> 10:09.200
We'll not find peace anywhere else

10:09.200 --> 10:10.863
until we find it here first.

10:11.808 --> 10:14.800
- [Mara] But I fear for
your safety if you stay.

10:14.800 --> 10:16.617
I know they mean to harm you.

10:17.998 --> 10:21.665
(emotional orchestra music)

11:18.840 --> 11:21.507
(ominous music)

11:24.206 --> 11:26.873
(keys jangling)

11:41.195 --> 11:44.862
(dramatic orchestral music)

11:52.013 --> 11:54.680
(phone ringing)

11:57.886 --> 12:00.170
(phone ringing)

12:00.170 --> 12:01.003
- Hello?

12:03.738 --> 12:04.588
Is someone there?

12:21.511 --> 12:24.511
(breathing heavily)

12:26.770 --> 12:28.230
- Hello?

12:28.230 --> 12:29.340
- [Holly] Mark?

12:29.340 --> 12:30.640
- Holly?

12:30.640 --> 12:31.610
- [Holly] Yeah.

12:31.610 --> 12:33.000
Did I catch you at a bad time?

12:33.000 --> 12:34.330
- Um, I'm...

12:34.330 --> 12:35.750
No, no, this is fine.

12:35.750 --> 12:37.510
What's up? Perfect time.

12:37.510 --> 12:38.820
- [Holly] Okay.

12:38.820 --> 12:40.263
I was just calling to say,

12:41.220 --> 12:44.820
I hope that you didn't feel
like we drowned you out today.

12:44.820 --> 12:45.930
You were kinda quiet.

12:45.930 --> 12:50.930
I know I can be loud, and he can be loud.

12:50.970 --> 12:53.493
And if we're gonna collaborate creatively,

12:54.380 --> 12:56.830
everybody needs to feel
like they're being heard.

12:58.880 --> 13:01.480
- Wow, that's really considerate of you

13:01.480 --> 13:03.270
to think about me like that.

13:03.270 --> 13:04.103
Thank you.

13:05.480 --> 13:09.870
If I'm being honest,
lately I've been sort of...

13:09.870 --> 13:12.970
stunted creatively and...

13:12.970 --> 13:13.803
otherwise.

13:13.803 --> 13:14.636
It's like I...

13:15.550 --> 13:18.820
I try to get out there,
you know, and step to it,

13:18.820 --> 13:21.280
and it's just like I just don't have

13:21.280 --> 13:25.520
any kind of motivation anymore
or inspiration, I don't know.

13:25.520 --> 13:26.743
It's my fault, I guess.

13:27.750 --> 13:28.583
- [Holly] No, no.

13:28.583 --> 13:30.933
I've felt the exact same way sometimes.

13:32.050 --> 13:33.700
And, you know, no pressure.

13:33.700 --> 13:35.270
I'm not trying to force you.

13:35.270 --> 13:37.660
You can't force creativity, but,

13:37.660 --> 13:39.310
you know, hopefully along the way

13:39.310 --> 13:43.770
you will rediscover some of
your creativity and passion,

13:43.770 --> 13:46.483
and hopefully I will get to see it.

13:48.050 --> 13:48.883
- Yeah.

13:50.320 --> 13:51.153
Thanks.

13:52.010 --> 13:53.080
Thanks.

13:53.080 --> 13:54.060
- [Holly] Anyway, that's it.

13:54.060 --> 13:56.850
I'll let you get back to
whatever it is you're doing,

13:56.850 --> 13:59.206
and see you at the next one.

13:59.206 --> 14:01.178
- Okay, yeah, see you then.

14:01.178 --> 14:03.595
(soft music)

14:08.896 --> 14:09.729
Huh.

14:16.814 --> 14:19.314
(eerie music)

14:29.101 --> 14:31.768
(ominous music)

14:39.541 --> 14:42.374
(heavy breathing)

15:01.254 --> 15:04.254
(suspenseful music)

15:25.949 --> 15:28.449
(music stops)

15:29.513 --> 15:31.930
(soft music)

15:37.098 --> 15:42.098
(ominous music)
(car honks)

15:42.770 --> 15:44.007
(dramatic music)
(woman gasps)

15:44.007 --> 15:46.674
(woman screams)

15:51.640 --> 15:53.140
- I'm gonna lose the fog,

15:53.140 --> 15:56.970
because I don't remember the
last time that we had a fog

15:56.970 --> 15:59.300
so thick you can barely see through it.

15:59.300 --> 16:02.620
- But that would look so good on camera!

16:02.620 --> 16:05.860
- I mean, maybe that's how it went.

16:08.501 --> 16:09.334
(slap)

16:09.334 --> 16:10.167
- Oh! God!

16:10.167 --> 16:11.000
Ow! Ow!

16:11.000 --> 16:12.035
Stop it! Stop it!

16:12.035 --> 16:14.170
(groaning)

16:14.170 --> 16:15.910
- Okay, well how about this?

16:15.910 --> 16:18.800
She's out on her late night jog, no fog.

16:18.800 --> 16:21.140
Our stalker's been after her all night.

16:21.140 --> 16:24.820
He's been sneaking around,
hiding behind bushes, trees.

16:24.820 --> 16:25.653
- Okay.

16:25.653 --> 16:26.560
- Until...

16:26.560 --> 16:27.713
he makes a mistake.

16:28.890 --> 16:30.610
He steps on a stick.

16:30.610 --> 16:32.250
She turns and notice, he panics!

16:32.250 --> 16:33.160
He chases after her!

16:33.160 --> 16:35.010
She runs to her nearest neighbor,

16:35.010 --> 16:36.128
starts beating on the door!

16:36.128 --> 16:38.370
"Help, help, someone's gonna kill me!"

16:38.370 --> 16:40.650
As the neighbor comes
through the door, boom!

16:40.650 --> 16:42.320
Knife through the back and out the stomach

16:42.320 --> 16:45.171
and blood goes everywhere!

16:45.171 --> 16:47.338
(panting)

16:50.020 --> 16:52.403
- Oh, that was for real? That was serious?

16:53.400 --> 16:54.610
That is...

16:54.610 --> 16:56.980
Did you read the articles on the kills?

16:56.980 --> 16:59.440
I mean, that's not even close.

16:59.440 --> 17:00.300
- I'm not...

17:01.360 --> 17:04.050
I'm not trying to be critical...

17:04.050 --> 17:05.163
but I'm gonna be.

17:06.120 --> 17:09.740
This sounds like a very
generic slasher film.

17:09.740 --> 17:11.170
- Generic?

17:11.170 --> 17:13.050
How is this generic?

17:13.050 --> 17:16.750
Look, what's different here
is that this could be anyone.

17:16.750 --> 17:18.130
It could be your neighbor.

17:18.130 --> 17:20.380
It could be your mom for all we know.

17:20.380 --> 17:22.423
- No, Seth, it couldn't.

17:23.590 --> 17:26.040
I think you're missing
what makes this whole thing

17:26.040 --> 17:27.590
interesting and special,

17:27.590 --> 17:30.380
and that's the fact that
it is a very specific story

17:30.380 --> 17:32.810
that couldn't happen to just anyone.

17:32.810 --> 17:35.975
The killer obviously has their own ideas.

17:35.975 --> 17:36.808
- Right.

17:36.808 --> 17:39.395
- And a very detail-oriented
way of doing this.

17:39.395 --> 17:40.228
- Exactly.

17:40.228 --> 17:41.160
- And we need to approach it

17:41.160 --> 17:43.006
with that same level of observation...

17:43.006 --> 17:43.839
- Thank you.

17:43.839 --> 17:45.350
- [Holly] If this is the
story that we want to tell.

17:45.350 --> 17:47.140
- Exactly. That's what I was gonna say.

17:47.140 --> 17:49.570
- And it couldn't happen
to my neighbor or my mom,

17:49.570 --> 17:51.440
because he has a type.

17:51.440 --> 17:53.710
He has a profile that
he has been following.

17:53.710 --> 17:55.100
And it's not just women.
- Right.

17:55.100 --> 17:56.030
- Or even women...
- No.

17:56.030 --> 17:57.620
- In a specific age demographic.

17:57.620 --> 17:59.506
He has consistently targeted women...

17:59.506 --> 18:00.339
- Right.

18:00.339 --> 18:01.373
- With flower names.
- That remind him of his mom.

18:02.415 --> 18:03.248
- What?
- What?

18:04.120 --> 18:05.470
- Oh, they all had flower names.

18:05.470 --> 18:07.560
You know, there was Mary-Rose Jones.

18:07.560 --> 18:08.920
There was Iris Johnson.

18:08.920 --> 18:10.763
And then there was Heather Beech.

18:12.324 --> 18:13.157
- Huh!

18:15.210 --> 18:16.983
Wow, that is something!

18:18.270 --> 18:20.180
- The murder-lizer.

18:20.180 --> 18:21.310
- What?

18:21.310 --> 18:23.997
- It's like fertilizer, but with murder.

18:23.997 --> 18:25.200
- No.
- No, that's...

18:25.200 --> 18:26.180
What?

18:26.180 --> 18:27.400
- The petal clipper.

18:27.400 --> 18:28.540
- Oh!

18:28.540 --> 18:29.740
- The petal-phile.

18:29.740 --> 18:30.810
- What? No!

18:30.810 --> 18:32.710
- The greenhouse strangler.

18:32.710 --> 18:33.950
- Awful.

18:33.950 --> 18:35.290
- The botanist.

18:35.290 --> 18:36.490
- Why are we doing this?

18:37.940 --> 18:39.433
- The gardener.

18:40.310 --> 18:41.940
- I don't hate gardener.

18:41.940 --> 18:42.920
- See?

18:42.920 --> 18:44.850
We don't have to decide
on the name right now,

18:44.850 --> 18:47.290
but we take the imagery of
someone slashing a flower

18:47.290 --> 18:48.670
then slashing a girl.

18:48.670 --> 18:51.430
Flower, girl, flower, girl.

18:51.430 --> 18:52.980
- No one gut slashed!

18:52.980 --> 18:53.813
- Thank you.

18:53.813 --> 18:55.780
- The cause of death was...

18:55.780 --> 18:56.730
strangulation.

18:56.730 --> 18:58.490
- Exactly, strangulation.

18:58.490 --> 19:00.770
There is, from what I read,

19:00.770 --> 19:03.290
a very certain intimacy with strangulation

19:03.290 --> 19:04.630
that's specific to the killer.

19:04.630 --> 19:06.770
That's the whole point, right?

19:06.770 --> 19:10.590
- Strangulation is boring!

19:10.590 --> 19:12.400
The fans, they want entertainment!

19:12.400 --> 19:16.053
They want blood, they want
screams, they want horror!

19:18.820 --> 19:20.410
You know what?

19:20.410 --> 19:21.610
Enough talking about it.

19:22.670 --> 19:23.543
I'll show you.

19:24.640 --> 19:25.473
Come outside.

19:29.401 --> 19:31.167
I'm not gonna slash you.

19:33.926 --> 19:36.593
(anxious music)

19:51.871 --> 19:52.901
(suspenseful music)

19:52.901 --> 19:54.920
(ax thuds)

19:54.920 --> 19:56.670
- Welcome, class!

19:56.670 --> 19:58.670
In today's lesson we will be talking

19:58.670 --> 20:00.880
about two different things.

20:00.880 --> 20:01.820
Fear...

20:02.770 --> 20:04.360
and compromise.

20:04.360 --> 20:07.020
For these lessons, I'll
need some assistance.

20:07.020 --> 20:07.993
Any volunteers?

20:09.370 --> 20:10.203
Holly?

20:14.991 --> 20:16.550
Ah, ah!

20:16.550 --> 20:17.383
Take a knee.

20:18.790 --> 20:20.290
- Can't wait for this lawsuit.

20:21.480 --> 20:23.070
- Lesson number one.

20:23.070 --> 20:24.520
Compromise.

20:24.520 --> 20:26.640
The articles say the
victims were dismembered

20:26.640 --> 20:27.600
post-mortem, correct?

20:27.600 --> 20:28.480
- Yes.

20:28.480 --> 20:29.730
I like that. I liked that.

20:29.730 --> 20:31.070
But...

20:31.070 --> 20:32.220
what do you say...

20:33.250 --> 20:36.090
we just moved the
timeline up a little bit?

20:36.090 --> 20:38.340
It still sticks to the dismemberment.

20:38.340 --> 20:42.239
It's just right before death
instead of right after.

20:42.239 --> 20:45.100
I think you can agree that
that's not too big of a jump.

20:45.100 --> 20:48.630
So, the killer has his victim tied up.

20:48.630 --> 20:53.070
The camera's from below,
shooting up on our killer,

20:53.070 --> 20:56.603
a position of dominance, of power!

20:57.860 --> 21:01.673
He takes her hand, tries to
build a little trust with her.

21:04.310 --> 21:05.373
He places it down.

21:06.270 --> 21:09.950
He starts, finger by...

21:09.950 --> 21:10.783
finger!

21:12.550 --> 21:15.133
Until she's nothing but
a bloody mess to hide.

